;; 4.1 Programming with Conditionals

; Taking a closer look at the general shape of the `cond` expression:
;
; (cond
;   [ConditionExpression1 ResultExpression1]   ; cond clause 1
;   [ConditionExpression2 ResultExpression2]   ; cond clause 2
;   ...
;   [ConditionExpressionN ResultExpressionN])  ; cond clause N

; Here's a function definition that uses a conditional expression:
(define (next traffic-light-state)
  (cond
    [(string=? "red"    traffic-light-state) "green" ]
    [(string=? "green"  traffic-light-state) "yellow"]
    [(string=? "yellow" traffic-light-state) "red"   ]))

; `cond` expressions allow the use of an `else` keyword for the last line:
;
; (cond
;   [ConditionExpression1 ResultExpression1]
;   [ConditionExpression2 ResultExpression2]
;   ...
;   [ConditionExpressionN ResultExpressionN]
;   [else DefaultResultExpression])

; IF you know that you want the exact opposite (i.e., the complement) of all
; previous conditions, use the `else` clause. It helps reduce the number of
; mistakes/bugs in your code.


